Singapore’s Labor Gaps May Drive Inflation  Says Morgan Stanley(Bloomberg) --Singapore is facing potential labor constraints that could pose upside risks to inflation  said economists fromMorgan Stanley  as officials in the city-state come under scrutiny to address a pandemic-driven shortfall in workers.Job vacancies have jumped above pre-Covid levels and wages have picked up much faster compared to the aftermath of the global financial crisis in 2008  which are “unusual” and hint at supply shortages  analysts led byDeyi Tanwrote in a research note this week.“This likely reflects how companies need workers but are unable to find them given smaller labor supply and perhaps to some degree  new types of jobs being created as the pandemic changes economies ” they said.Data due next week will probably show consumer price growth in the countryremained elevatedin December  following November’s print that recorded the largest gains -- both on month-on-month and year-on-year terms -- since February 2013.
